body:
~~So now I'm confused.~~ I extended the existing test for decorating `default` methods to this:

```java
public class DecoratorDefaultMethodNotImplementedTest {
    @RegisterExtension
    public ArcTestContainer container = new ArcTestContainer(Converter.class, ToLengthConverter.class,
            Add1ConverterDecorator.class);

    @Test
    public void testDecoration() {
        Converter<String> converter = Arc.container().instance(new TypeLiteral<Converter<String>>() {
        }).get();
        assertEquals(6, converter.convert("Hola!"));
        assertEquals(6, converter.convert("Hola!", true));
    }

    interface Converter<T> {
        int convert(T value);

        default int convert(T value, boolean ignored) {
            return convert(value);
        }
    }

    @ApplicationScoped
    static class ToLengthConverter implements Converter<String> {
        @Override
        public int convert(String value) {
            return value.length();
        }
    }

    @Priority(1)
    @Decorator
    static class Add1ConverterDecorator implements Converter<String> {
        @Inject
        @Delegate
        Converter<String> delegate;

        @Override
        public int convert(String value) {
            return 1 + delegate.convert(value);
        }
    }
}
```

And the test passes. ~~Which is I think what you expected, even though it goes kinda sorta against the specification?~~

EDIT: actually it doesn't go against the spec. The `default` method forwards to an abstract method, which is what gets decorated. The `default` method itself is not. So it's OK.

In your example the decorator does not override the default method, but the abstract method. Just override the default method in the decorator and return 0 without any delegating any call. Your test should fail with the actual returned value also being 0 (because the decorator hardcoded this return value), but still returning 6 as the default method is being invoked, which delegates to the abstract method, which in turn is also decorated and added 1 to the computed result.

```java
@Priority(1)
@Decorator
static class Add1ConverterDecorator implements Converter<String> {

  private Converter<String> delegate;

  Add1ConverterDecorator(@Delegate Converter<String> delegate) {
      this.delegate = delegate;
  }

  @Override
  public int convert(String value) {
      return 1 + delegate.convert(value);
  }

  @Override
  public int convert(String value, boolean ignored) {
      return 0;
  }
}
```

For reference, if I would setup the docoration chain programmatically myself (which could be exported as an bean via a producer method), invocations of the default method would return the expected result:

```java
@Test
void testProgrammanticDecoration() {
    var converter = new Add1ConverterDecorator(new ToLengthConverter());

    assertEquals(6, converter.convert("Hola!"));
    assertEquals(0, converter.convert("Hola!", true));
}
```

I would assume nobody would argue against the behavior of the last programmatic decoration example, because that is just [plain old java code](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decorator_pattern#Java) from schools when learning how to implement this GoF pattern.
